## ASP.NET Framework → ASP.NET Core 8 Migration

### Key Breaking Changes

1. **`Response.End()` / `Response.Redirect(..., true)`** — these relied on `Thread.Abort`, which **does not exist** in .NET Core. No `ThreadAbortException` is thrown.
2. **`Response.Write()`** — replaced by writing to `Response.Body` or returning `IActionResult`.
3. **WebForms event model** (`btnExport_Click`) — gone entirely. Use MVC action methods.
4. **`Response.Clear()` / `AddHeader()`** — replaced by `Response.Headers` and `IActionResult` return types.

### Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Authorization;
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;

public class ReportController : Controller
{
    // POST /Report/Export
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Export()
    {
        var data = GenerateReport();

        // FileContentResult handles Content-Type, Content-Disposition,
        // and writing to the response body — no Response.End() needed.
        return File(
            System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data),
            "text/csv",
            "report.csv"
        );
    }

    // POST /Report/Redirect
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult RedirectAction()
    {
        // In Core, check authentication via the User principal
        // or use [Authorize]. No Thread.Abort involved.
        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            return RedirectToAction("Index", "Login"); // or Redirect("/login")
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        // NOTE: Do NOT catch ThreadAbortException — it doesn't exist in .NET Core.
        // Catching it was only necessary because Response.Redirect threw it.
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            LogError(ex);
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }

    private string GenerateReport() => /* ... */ "";
    private void ProcessRequest() { /* ... */ }
    private void LogError(Exception ex) { /* ... */ }
}
```

### Common Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Catching `ThreadAbortException`** | Remove all `catch (ThreadAbortException)` blocks. They are dead code in Core and mask the fact that the control flow has fundamentally changed. |
| **Code after `Response.Redirect`** | In Framework with `endResponse: true`, code after `Redirect` never ran. In Core, `Redirect("/x")` just sets a 302 header — **code continues executing**. Always `return Redirect(...)`. |
| **`Response.End()` replacements** | Don't call `HttpContext.Response.CompleteAsync()` as a drop-in — it flushes but doesn't stop execution. Return an `IActionResult` instead. |
| **`Response.Write()` for files** | Use `File()`, `PhysicalFile()`, or `FileStreamResult`. They handle headers and streaming correctly, and support range requests. |
| **Authentication checks** | Prefer `[Authorize]` attribute over manual `IsAuthenticated` checks. Configure in `Program.cs`: |

```csharp
// Program.cs
builder.Services.AddAuthentication(/* scheme */);
builder.Services.AddAuthorization();

var app = builder.Build();
app.UseAuthentication();
app.UseAuthorization();
```

Then simplify:

```csharp
[Authorize]
[HttpPost]
public IActionResult RedirectAction()
{
    // No auth check needed — framework returns 401/redirects automatically
    try
    {
        ProcessRequest();
        return Redirect("/success");
    }
    catch (Exception ex)
    {
        LogError(ex);
        return Redirect("/error");
    }
}
```

### The Core Principle

In Framework, `Response.Redirect/End` **aborted the thread** to stop execution. In Core, action methods use a **return-value model** — you `return` an `IActionResult` and the framework handles the HTTP response. Any code after a `Redirect()` call without `return` **will still execute**, which is the single most common source of bugs during migration.
